{
    "course_code": "ECON 695",
    "course_title": "Data Analysis and Big Data",
    "credits": "3",
    "course_description": "This course teaches students how to extract economically meaningful information from data on a scale beyond what basic data-processing software packages (Excel, Access, SPSS) are designed to handle. It is designed for the novice programmer writing code in Python and emphasizes work with spatially detailed data, which provides social scientists with records that describe the who, what, when, and where of human behavior. Students will gain the necessary proficiency with Python programming to record, manipulate, organize, and analyze extremely large datasets. The course will also feature hands-on Geographic Information Systems (GIS) training that will teach students to evaluate and visually represent spatial data.",
    "course_summary": "- Learn to use Python for large-scale data manipulation\n- GIS training for economic data analysis\n- Project-based learning with a focus on real-world applications",
    "learning_outcomes": "- Acquire skills in statistical and computational techniques\n- Analyze real world situations and policies with computational techniques\n- Critically evaluate public policy proposals with economic analysis\n- Gain interest in leveraging large datasets for economic analysis\n- Evaluate economic outcomes with GIS technology\n- Develop project management experience\n- Engage with professional communities for big data",
    "what_you_will_learn": "- Proficiency in Python programming for big data analysis\n- Implementation of GIS in economic research\n- Project management and collaboration skills\n- Application of big data techniques to real-world economic issues",
